04524nam a22006855i 9781442653580DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20171978onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426535807 a10.3138/97814426535802doi  a(DE-B1597)479287  a(OCoLC)992466236  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPR3069.D57bD3 7aLIT0150002bisacsh04a822.3/31 aDawson, Anthony, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIndirections :bShakespeare and the Art of illusion /cAnthony Dawson. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2017] 4c©1978  a1 online resource (210 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Merchant of Venice -- t2. As You Like It -- t3. Hamlet -- t4. A Midsummer Night's Dream, Twelfth Night, and Troilus and Cressida -- t5. All's Well that Ends Well -- t6. Measure for Measure -- t7. King Lear, Antony and Cleopatra, and The Winter's Tale -- t8. The Tempest -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe precise relation between the spectator and the work of art was a matter of great interest to late Renaissance and baroque artists, playwrights as well as painters. In Shakespeare's plays the relation between audience and stage life is crucial. The plays constantly remind the audience of the complex fictiveness of their experience yet they also project a reality specifically through illusion. Indirections is a study of twelve plays in which Shakespeare sets up situations and relationships between the characters analogous to the relationship established between audience and play. This book examines the varied uses of illusion, deceit, disguise, and manipulation in the plays, both comedies and tragedies, and traces Shakespeare's use of illusion through his career — from the buoyant optimism of the great comedies and the ambiguity of the middle years to the new richness and power in the romances. Dawson suggests that the way characters respond to illusory situations sets up a model for the way audiences are meant to respond to the play themselves. Such action at least initially establishes a basis for the movement of characters from self-delusion to self-knowledge. This process of self-realization enables the characters to distinguish truth from appearance, love from infatuation; and significantly, it is a direct result of involvement with illusion and role-playing. It is as if the characters must arrive, within the movement of the plot, at an understanding of, and response to, the nature of drama itself parallel to the audience's experience of the play as a whole. This subtle interplay between audience and characters, where each in a sense represents the other, depends for its life on the physical and psychic distances created by the theatre.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDisguise in literature. 0aIllusion in literature. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144265358040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442653580423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442653580.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK